Rules:
1. Use integer times only; duration uses `math.ceil`.
2. Use
   `resource_usage = defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(lambda: 0)))`
3. Ignore resource `r` if `work_volume[r] == 0` or `demand_min[r] == demand_max[r] == 0`.
4. A contractor is invalid for a job if any relevant `r` is missing in `workers` or `workers[r] < demand_min[r]`.
5. For contractor `c` on interval `[start_time, end_time)`:
   `allocated[r] = min(demand_max[r], min_t(workers[r] - resource_usage[c][t][r]))`
   If any slot has availability `< demand_min[r]`, this contractor is infeasible.
6. Compute duration only at scheduling time:
   `duration = max_r ceil(work_volume[r] / productivity[r])`
   where `productivity[r] = allocated[r] * communication_coefficient(allocated[r], demand_max[r])` if provided, else `allocated[r]`
7. A job becomes eligible only after all predecessors finish.
8. At each `current_time`:
   - complete finished jobs and unlock successors
   - collect eligible unscheduled jobs
   - try to schedule each eligible job
   - if nothing scheduled, advance to the minimum end_time among active jobs
   - if no active jobs and unscheduled jobs remain, raise `ValueError("Deadlock detected")`
9. For each eligible job, collect feasible contractors at `current_time`, then choose:
   smallest `sum(workers.values())`, tie -> lexicographically smallest contractor id
10. Before scheduling, ensure every job has at least one contractor satisfying minimum demand on all relevant resources; otherwise raise `ValueError`.
11. Enforce wall-clock limit: 10 seconds.

